{"key":"post-8969038","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>8969038</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Stick with rye grain for substrate for spawn running and Peat/verm or enriched equine dung for casing.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This is why so many people mess up their grows.&amp;nbsp; Horse manure is NOT a casing, and too many people around here are not familiar with the nomenclature of cultivation.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Peat/verm is used as a casing layer, but is entirely optional when you've spawned to a bulk substrate.&amp;nbsp; The only time you'd really need a casing layer with cubensis is if you wanted to fruit from straight rye berries or wbs.&amp;nbsp; In that case, you'd lay the grains out in a tray, and cover with 1/2&quot; of pasteurized casing material.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A substrate is what you actually grow the mushrooms on.&amp;nbsp; Items like straw, manure, worm castings, coir, etc., are all examples of substrate.&amp;nbsp; When using these for substrate, you inoculate it with your fully colonized pf cakes or rye grains, which are your &lt;i&gt;spawn&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When using a bulk substrate to grow cubensis, a casing layer is optional, and quite frankly in my experience, you'll do as well without a casing by maintaining proper fruiting parameters.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>8969106</next>\n<prev>8968820</prev>\n<first>8968728</first>\n<last>8970853</last>\n<when>1222125234</when>\n<utime>09/23/08 02:13 AM</utime>\n</post>"}